 o  device usage

 o  oo-modules, here's what its suggestor says about it:

Well, the basic concept is to build several objects that are abstract enough
to be included in most everyone's work.  For example, each of the libraries
one opens up could have objects of their own that are derived from a single
'library' object, which itself would have OpenLibrary/CloseLibrary routines.
A derived class of such a library could be 'devices' which, instead of opening
or closing a library could open/close a device.

Then, further developing this, one could build a serial-port object derived
from the devices object.

All the while, a kind of 'i/o' object could be written which could handle all
the different kinds of input and output one might expect in a stream-oriented
kind of way.  One could then derive a 'serial' object from this, which would
make heavy use of the library/devices/serial object.  This same 'i/o' object
could also have a derived object of 'file', or whatever.

The big job would be to get the Amiga's environment set up as a series of
useful objects, which requires we figure out a kind of hiearchy (sic?)
associated to the Amiga environment.

- Trey


